### Convergence of Sequences & Series

A sequence of real numbers \(u_{1}\), \(u_{2}\), \(u_{3}\),... is said to **converge** to a real number \(a\) if \(u_{s}\to a\) as \(n\to\infty\).

For example, the sequence \(u_{s}=1+\frac{1}{2^{s}}\) for \(n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\) converges to \(1\) as \(n\to\infty\). Thus, we say that \(1\) is the limit of the sequence \(u_{s}=1+\frac{1}{2^{s}}\) for \(n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\).

Mathematically, we can write \(\lim_{n\to\infty}u_{s}=\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(1+\frac{1}{2^{s}}\right)=1\).

However, the sequence \(u_{s}=2^{s}\) for \(n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\) does not have a limit, i.e. the sequence \(u_{s}=2^{s}\) for \(n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\)**diverges**.

