**1. Arithmetic Progression (AP)**

An **arithmetic progression** is a sequence in which each term (other than the first term) differs from the previous one by the same fixed number (positive or negative or zero) known as **common difference**, \(d\).

Examples of AP:

(a) 2, 5, 8, 11,... is an AP with first term, \(a=2\) and common difference, \(d=3\)

(b) 6, \(-4\), \(-14\), \(-24\),... is an AP with first term, \(a=6\) and common difference, \(d=-10\)

(c) \(-1\), \(-\dfrac{2}{3}\), \(-\dfrac{1}{3}\), \(0\), \(\dfrac{1}{3}\),... is an AP with first term, \(a=-1\) and common difference, \(d=\dfrac{1}{3}\).

**Question:** Is the sequence 1, 1, 1, 1,... an AP?

**Note:** An AP is completely defined by the first term \(a\) and the common difference \(d\).

In general, if an AP has first term \(a\) and common difference \(d\), then the AP can be written as

\[a,\qquad a+d,\qquad a+2d,\qquad a+3d,\qquad a+4d,\,...\]

\(u_{1}=a\)

\(u_{2}=a+d\)

\(u_{3}=a+2d\)

\(u_{4}=a\,+3d\)

\(\vdots\)

In general, the \(n^{\text{th}}\) term of an AP can be written as

\[\boxed{\mathbf{u_{n}=a+(n-1)d,\ n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}}}\]

