An **arithmetic series** is the sum of the terms of an arithmetic progression.

Recall that \(S_{n}\) is the sum of the first \(n\) terms in a sequence.

For an AP, the formula of \(S_{n}\) is given by

\[S_{n} = \frac{n}{2}\Big{[}2a\ +\ \big{(}n-1\big{)}d\Big{]}\] \[= \frac{n}{2}\big{(}a+\ l\big{)},\,\text{where}\ l\ \text{is the last term}\]

**Proof (Independent Reading):**

\[S_{n}=\ a+(a+d)+(a+2d)+(a+3d)+(a+4d)+\cdots+[a+(n-2)d]+[a+(n-1)d]\]

We can write the series in two different manner:

\[S_{n}= a+\quad(a+d)+\cdots+[a+(n-2)d]+[a+(n-1)d]\] \[S_{n}= [a+(n-1)d]+[a+(n-2)d]+\cdots+\quad\quad a+d+\quad\quad a\]

Adding these two equations, we have

\[2S_{n}=\underbrace{[2a+(n-1)d]+[2a+(n-1)d]+\cdots+[2a+(n-1)d+[2a+(n-1)d]}_{n \text{ of such terms}}\]

Thus, \(2S_{n}=n[2a+(n-1)d]\)

\[\Rightarrow\quad S_{n}= \frac{n}{2}[2a+(n-1)d]\] \[= \frac{n}{2}[a+a+(n-1)d]\] \[= \frac{n}{2}[a+l]\quad\text{ where}\ l=a+\big{(}n-1\big{)}d\ \ \text{is the}\ n^{\text{th}}\ \text{(or last) term of the sequence}\]

This method of finding \(S_{n}\) of an AP is known as the Gaussian method.

